					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On December 31, 2005 at 10:15 PM, LittleJohn (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>ROUX?!?!?!?!?</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">All this debate about how to prepare the roux is silly - New England clam chowder should NOT be thickened with roux.  Roux thickening is an ill-advised "innovation" introduced in the 1950s and popularized by HoJo's.  Truly traditional chowder (at least since potatoes replaced pounded seabiscuit ~150 years ago) is thickened by simmering the potatoes until they contribute some starchiness.  It is also thinner (I would say less glue-like) than what you get at most restaurants these days.<br />
<br />
I actually prefer canned chopped (not minced) sea clams to whole canned clams, but I'll take quahogs in the shell over any of the above.  If you heat the milk gently (just until warm) before you add it to the chowder, it won't separate.<br />
<br />
In other news, Yukon Golds make great chowder potatoes.</div>
