					<div class="commentheading">On October 28, 2010 at 09:44 PM, dbeem (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody">A roux is an essential part of French cooking and is therefore an essential part of Cajun cooking.  This was adapted into southern cooking.  I repeat: <i>SOUTHERN</i> COOKING.  This is why a roux is not used in traditional New England clam chowder.  Nothing is to stop anyone from using a roux in clam chowder, but if a roux is used, don't consider what you have made to be <i>traditional</i> New England clam chowder.</div>
